for Hogan Assessment Systems. OK, so practical

00:39:55.670 --> 00:40:00.760
approaches for leaders. Be a blame-savvy boss.
So, think about credit and blame, the dynamics

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:05.890
of credit and blame on your team. And be mindful
of how you're assigning it, how other people

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:12.140
are assigning it. Take an open and adaptive
approach rather than blaming people.

00:40:12.140 --> 00:40:16.400
Think about how can we focus on solutions
rather than on problems, realizing that you're

00:40:16.400 --> 00:40:21.720
setting an example with everything you do,
or don't do. Fight group think. So, try to

00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:27.579
think about--. It's gonna be tempting for
people who report to you to become Yes Men

00:40:27.579 --> 00:40:29.979
and Women and tell you everything you're doing
is great.

00:40:29.979 --> 00:40:34.769
So, you have to keep in mind that sort of
social hierarchy and people's intimidation

00:40:34.769 --> 00:40:39.529
and ask people questions like, "Well, if this
doesn't work, why wouldn't it work?" Or maybe

00:40:39.529 --> 00:40:45.460
you assign people randomly to argue for or
against an initiative or a project that you're

00:40:45.460 --> 00:40:51.049
considering just so there's a forum for that,
so people will feel, again, safe to speak

00:40:51.049 --> 00:40:55.229
up even if they don't feel comfortable.

00:40:55.229 --> 00:41:00.109
Focus on systems and situations. So think
about when you're talking with people about

00:41:00.109 --> 00:41:04.299
their performance and what made it go well,
or didn't go well. What are the contextual

00:41:04.299 --> 00:41:08.690
factors? And how can you, as a leader, get
them more resources or support or information

00:41:08.690 --> 00:41:12.750
so that they can be more successful going
forward.

00:41:12.750 --> 00:41:17.609
Get and keep the right people on the bus.
So when you're hiring people, try to ascertain

00:41:17.609 --> 00:41:22.450
how do they do in terms of credit and blame.
Are they unduly crediting themselves? Are

00:41:22.450 --> 00:41:27.259
they saying "I" when they really mean "we?"
Or maybe they're too modest and self-effacing

00:41:27.259 --> 00:41:30.660
and they're saying "we" when they really mean
"I?"

00:41:30.660 --> 00:41:36.130
But looking at people's pattern credit and
blame can be a great diagnostic as to whether

00:41:36.130 --> 00:41:41.029
they'll be a good person to have reporting
to you or to have working with you. And the

00:41:41.029 --> 00:41:46.320
last recommendation is to write a managerial
user's manual for your new team. And what

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:48.380
this is, is a document. It can be informal.

00:41:48.380 --> 00:41:54.369
You can share it in writing or just verbally,
which is, "I'm your new boss. Here's what

00:41:54.369 --> 00:41:58.759
you need to know about me. Here's what people
are likely to misunderstand about me." And

00:41:58.759 --> 00:42:02.819
the reason this is relevant to credit and
blame is because people size each other up.

00:42:02.819 --> 00:42:07.609
There can be cross-cultural miscommunications.
So, if I'm your new boss and I ask you a lot

00:42:07.609 --> 00:42:13.239
of questions, you might panic and you might
assume that I don't trust you, that I'm trying

00:42:13.239 --> 00:42:14.259
to get rid of you.

00:42:14.259 --> 00:42:19.079
I'm asking a lot of questions and you might
get worried that this is really about me determining

00:42:19.079 --> 00:42:24.180
who to fire. But if I say to you, "It's my
style to ask a lot of questions. It doesn't

00:42:24.180 --> 00:42:28.420
mean that I don't trust you. It doesn't mean
that I'm trying to diagnose your capabilities.

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:33.910
I just ask a lot of questions." I have one
client who wrote a managerial user's manual.

00:42:33.910 --> 00:42:38.759
She told her team, "I'm British, so I tend
to be reserved. And Americans tend to think

00:42:38.759 --> 00:42:45.559
I'm standoffish and aloof. But I'm not. I'm
just British, so come talk to me anytime."

00:42:45.559 --> 00:42:51.819
And there are other things like that where
people might say for example, "I like information,

00:42:51.819 --> 00:42:57.460
even if it's unfinalized. So don't wait until
the last minute. Give me updates. I like updates.

00:42:57.460 --> 00:43:00.400
Give me an update, even if the update is 'there's
no update.'"

00:43:00.400 --> 00:43:05.499
And that way, there doesn't have to be tension
because you're not giving the manager what

00:43:05.499 --> 00:43:11.769
he or she wants. So having this thing can
avoid misunderstandings and what I call in

00:43:11.769 --> 00:43:17.170
the book, "mondegreens," which are when things
are misunderstood. And two famous stories

00:43:17.170 --> 00:43:22.920
about that was Winston Churchill, during the
Second World War, was referring to a person

00:43:22.920 --> 00:43:26.059
and he said to his staff, "Bring me Berlin."

00:43:26.059 --> 00:43:31.150
Not the city, the person. So they bring this
man to his office and Winston Churchill says

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:34.869
to him, "So what's the latest thing you've
been working on?" And the guy says, "A song

00:43:34.869 --> 00:43:40.099
called White Christmas." And in fact, Churchill
had wanted them to bring him Isaiah Berlin,

00:43:40.099 --> 00:43:43.569
the great philosopher, but they brought him
Irving Berlin.

00:43:43.569 --> 00:43:48.329
And there's another story about Herbert Hoover,
who had a rigid rule that there had to be

00:43:48.329 --> 00:43:54.380
one-inch margins on every memo that was sent
to him. And some hapless FBI leader sent him

00:43:54.380 --> 00:43:59.049
some note and where he proposed something,
but there was a lot of information so the

00:43:59.049 --> 00:44:03.970
margins were thinner. And so Hoover said,
"Your plan is fine, but watch the borders."

00:44:03.970 --> 00:44:08.019
And what he meant was watch the borders of
your memo, but instead, they panicked and

00:44:08.019 --> 00:44:12.819
they sent FBI agents to the Rio Grande and
to Saskatchewan, or whatever, to watch the

00:44:12.819 --> 00:44:16.769
borders because they thought he meant watch
the borders of the United States. So as a

00:44:16.769 --> 00:44:22.329
leader, if people are intimidated by you,
if you're blaming, you paradoxically are less

00:44:22.329 --> 00:44:26.960
likely to get what you want because people
aren't gonna approach you and ask for clarification.

00:44:26.960 --> 00:44:32.230
They're gonna instead bring you the wrong
person and engage in the wrong task-based

00:44:32.230 --> 00:44:37.859
behavior. And so, a user's manual breaks the
ice and makes sure that people feel comfortable

00:44:37.859 --> 00:44:42.890
approaching you and that there aren't those
cascading misunderstandings of blame that

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:44.920
then will lead to poor results.

